1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000


2
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,279
Imagine you have a time machine.

3
00:00:01,699 --> 00:00:04,140
Not a normal one, a perfect time machine.

4
00:00:04,530 --> 00:00:06,730
One that can travel back through every moment in

5
00:00:06,730 --> 00:00:10,390
history. You go back one year, then 1,000 years,

6
00:00:10,390 --> 00:00:11,109
then a million.

7
00:00:11,590 --> 00:00:13,789
Dinosaurs appear, then the earth disappears

8
00:00:13,789 --> 00:00:15,839
completely. You keep going.

9
00:00:15,860 --> 00:00:17,380
The sun hasn't formed yet.

10
00:00:17,380 --> 00:00:18,860
The Milky Way doesn't exist.

11
00:00:19,019 --> 00:00:21,539
No stars, no planets, no galaxies.

12
00:00:22,109 --> 00:00:24,810
Just a hot, dense universe shrinking smaller and

13
00:00:24,810 --> 00:00:26,950
smaller as you travel backward through time.

14
00:00:27,239 --> 00:00:29,640
You keep going. 10 billion years,

15
00:00:29,640 --> 00:00:33,220
12 billion years, 13 billion years, and then...

16
00:00:33,509 --> 00:00:34,570
You reach the Big Bang.

17
00:00:35,039 --> 00:00:36,540
The moment everything began.

18
00:00:36,699 --> 00:00:38,960
The moment space itself was born.

19
00:00:39,169 --> 00:00:41,210
the moment time itself started ticking.

20
00:00:41,650 --> 00:00:43,329
Naturally, the next question is:

21
00:00:43,590 --> 00:00:44,869
What was there before that?

22
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:46,860
And this is where things get weird,

23
00:00:46,860 --> 00:00:48,960
because according to our current understanding of

24
00:00:48,960 --> 00:00:52,000
physics, The answer might actually be nothing.

25
00:00:52,849 --> 00:00:55,529
not empty space. not darkness.

26
00:00:55,770 --> 00:00:57,970
Not a giant explosion waiting to happen.

27
00:00:58,450 --> 00:01:01,279
Nothing. Because the Big Bang wasn't an explosion

28
00:01:01,279 --> 00:01:02,839
that happened inside space.

29
00:01:03,429 --> 00:01:05,949
The Big Bang was the creation of space itself.

30
00:01:06,629 --> 00:01:07,670
Think about it this way:

31
00:01:08,039 --> 00:01:10,440
Asking what was before the Big Bang might be like

32
00:01:10,440 --> 00:01:12,860
asking,"What's north of the North Pole?"

33
00:01:13,459 --> 00:01:15,699
At first it sounds like a reasonable question,

34
00:01:16,019 --> 00:01:18,519
But the closer you look, the less sense it makes.

35
00:01:19,029 --> 00:01:21,010
The North Pole is the northernmost point.

36
00:01:21,359 --> 00:01:22,879
There is no north beyond it.

37
00:01:23,620 --> 00:01:26,360
Similarly, if time itself began at the Big Bang,

38
00:01:26,579 --> 00:01:29,359
There may have been no"before"for anything to

39
00:01:29,359 --> 00:01:32,549
exist in, No time. No events.

40
00:01:32,809 --> 00:01:34,829
No waiting. know before.

41
00:01:35,340 --> 00:01:37,540
But not every scientist agrees that's the end of

42
00:01:37,540 --> 00:01:37,959
the story.

43
00:01:38,579 --> 00:01:41,039
Some theories suggest there actually was something

44
00:01:41,039 --> 00:01:42,279
before the Big Bang.

45
00:01:42,709 --> 00:01:44,590
One idea is called the big bounce.

46
00:01:45,169 --> 00:01:47,490
According to this theory, our universe may not be

47
00:01:47,490 --> 00:01:48,289
the first universe.

48
00:01:48,959 --> 00:01:51,699
Instead, a previous universe existed long before

49
00:01:51,699 --> 00:01:55,100
ours. Over trillions of years, it slowly collapsed

50
00:01:55,100 --> 00:01:57,749
inward, smaller. Denser.

51
00:01:58,060 --> 00:02:00,900
hotter. until eventually it reached an extreme

52
00:02:00,900 --> 00:02:02,780
state and bounced outward again.

53
00:02:03,179 --> 00:02:05,059
Creating the universe we see today.

54
00:02:05,499 --> 00:02:07,459
In this picture, the Big Bang wasn't the

55
00:02:07,459 --> 00:02:09,620
beginning. It was just a restart button.

56
00:02:10,169 --> 00:02:12,429
Like the universe taking a cosmic breath,

57
00:02:12,819 --> 00:02:16,180
in Out. again and again forever.

58
00:02:16,800 --> 00:02:18,660
But wait! It gets even stranger.

59
00:02:19,389 --> 00:02:21,949
Another theory suggests our universe might be only

60
00:02:21,949 --> 00:02:24,610
one bubble in an enormous cosmic ocean.

61
00:02:25,069 --> 00:02:26,509
Imagine boiling water.

62
00:02:26,799 --> 00:02:29,059
Bubbles constantly appear and disappear.

63
00:02:29,439 --> 00:02:31,959
Now replace the water with an unimaginably vast

64
00:02:31,959 --> 00:02:32,519
reality.

65
00:02:33,060 --> 00:02:35,299
and replace the bubbles with entire universes.

66
00:02:36,039 --> 00:02:39,240
each one having its own stars, its own galaxies,

67
00:02:39,569 --> 00:02:41,310
maybe even its own laws of physics.

68
00:02:41,839 --> 00:02:44,099
Our universe could simply be one bubble among

69
00:02:44,099 --> 00:02:45,239
countless others.

70
00:02:45,599 --> 00:02:48,229
And if that's true, The Big Bang may have been the

71
00:02:48,229 --> 00:02:50,150
moment our particular bubble was born.

72
00:02:50,580 --> 00:02:52,080
Not the moment everything began.

73
00:02:52,749 --> 00:02:54,890
Then there's perhaps the strangest possibility of

74
00:02:54,890 --> 00:02:58,100
all: Some physicists think time itself may be an

75
00:02:58,100 --> 00:03:00,930
illusion. At the deepest level of reality,

76
00:03:00,930 --> 00:03:03,700
there may be no past. No future.

77
00:03:03,849 --> 00:03:05,269
No flow of time at all.

78
00:03:05,729 --> 00:03:07,910
What we experience as time could simply emerge

79
00:03:07,910 --> 00:03:10,050
from something more fundamental that we don't yet

80
00:03:10,050 --> 00:03:10,570
understand.

81
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:13,799
In that case, asking what happened before the Big

82
00:03:13,799 --> 00:03:16,299
Bang could be like asking what color the number 7

83
00:03:16,299 --> 00:03:19,330
is. The question itself may not fit the rules of

84
00:03:19,330 --> 00:03:21,530
reality. And here's the truth:

85
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:23,980
Nobody knows which answer is correct.

86
00:03:24,379 --> 00:03:25,179
Not yet.

87
00:03:25,629 --> 00:03:27,709
The Big Bang is where our current theories begin

88
00:03:27,709 --> 00:03:31,170
to break down. General relativity tells one story.

89
00:03:31,469 --> 00:03:33,110
Quantum Mechanics tells another:

90
00:03:33,469 --> 00:03:35,569
And when we push both theories back to the very

91
00:03:35,569 --> 00:03:38,220
beginning, The math stops making sense.

92
00:03:38,779 --> 00:03:40,739
Somewhere beyond that wall lies one of the

93
00:03:40,739 --> 00:03:42,439
greatest mysteries in science.

94
00:03:42,819 --> 00:03:44,420
So what was there before the Big Bang?

95
00:03:45,049 --> 00:03:47,420
Maybe nothing. Maybe another universe.

96
00:03:48,049 --> 00:03:50,590
Maybe an infinite cycle of cosmic rebirths.

97
00:03:51,099 --> 00:03:53,480
Maybe countless universes beyond our own.

98
00:03:53,759 --> 00:03:56,200
Or maybe the question itself has no answer because

99
00:03:56,200 --> 00:03:57,539
time didn't exist yet,

100
00:03:58,039 --> 00:04:00,240
The most incredible part is that right now,

101
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,739
somewhere on Earth, scientists are searching for

102
00:04:02,739 --> 00:04:04,960
clues. Studying Ancient Light

103
00:04:05,439 --> 00:04:07,039
Building powerful telescopes.

104
00:04:07,529 --> 00:04:09,630
trying to uncover evidence that could reveal what

105
00:04:09,630 --> 00:04:11,090
happened before the beginning.

106
00:04:11,520 --> 00:04:14,559
And perhaps one day, humanity will finally know.

107
00:04:14,989 --> 00:04:17,610
Until then, The biggest mystery in the universe

108
00:04:17,610 --> 00:04:19,749
remains the one that came before the universe

109
00:04:19,749 --> 00:04:20,269
itself.

